All right, my rundown on Vegas as a guy who goes there for work all the time:

• My hotel of choice: <https://www.google.com/maps/place/Hampton+Inn+Tropicana/@36.0991749,-115.1856974,16.08z/data=!4m8!3m7!1s0x80c8c5d4a67b25db:0x1a38e43716025f28!5m2!4m1!1i2!8m2!3d36.0996675!4d-115.1833771> (Cheap but not "I'm gonna get stabbed" cheap, can walk to the strip or take a shuttle every hour or so)
• Tram Tickets are $10/ride, or $15/day, and will take you wherever on the strip.  Lyft/Uber is pretty reasonable as well if you want to save yourself a walk.
• The Strip is a trap, and is actually not nearly as much fun as a lot of the things off of it. Check out the Neon museum with all of the old signs, right next to the Natural History Museum on N Las Vegas Blvd. Or, check out the pinball museum near the strip, basically on the UNLV campus. Bring quarters, they have it organized by decade and you can play all of the machines. If you're gonna go out for fun, do it on Fremont Street, the prices are a bit cheaper there. If you're just coming to gamble and not do Vegas things, the Aliante on the North Side has all of that and a hotel attached to it for about $150/night depending on if there's anything going on.
• If you're gonna stay in and do magic/other free things with folks, that's some of the best decision making you can make in Vegas. I'd still bring some extra cash with you, as you'll probably want to go out to at least one restaurant or go out with friends to see at least one thing.
• I've kind of warned people away from the strip here, but I really am a sucker for the Bellagio fountain. The show happens every 15 minutes. Don't bother trying to walk all the way to the middle, they've set up a VIP tent there in recent years so that people can have a "private" viewing experience.
All in all, it occurs to me that I should've given this rundown weeks ago, but most people were planning on just hanging out at the convention center I know.
